                <p><supplied reason="lost">Ἀγαθῆι</supplied> <supplied reason="lost">τύ</supplied>χηι. Ἔτους γ<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">ϙ</supplied> 
               <lb/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
               <supplied reason="lost">τῶι</supplied> <supplied reason="lost">Ὑψίστ</supplied>ωι Διὶ Βακ<lb break="no"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Αἴας Νικο<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
               <lb/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>λίνου κατ’ <supplied reason="lost">εὐ</supplied><lb break="no"/><supplied reason="lost">χὴν</supplied> <supplied reason="lost">τὸν</supplied> ναὸν ἐκ τ<supplied reason="lost">ῶν</supplied>
               <lb/><supplied reason="lost">ἰδίων</supplied> ἀνέθηκ<supplied reason="lost">εν</supplied></p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" ana="b1">
                <p>With good luck. Year 93 (?). Aias son of Nica.., following a vow, dedicated the
                    shrine to Zeus Bac.. at his own expenses.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The script is square, with classic omega and use of iota adscriptum. The modesty
                    of the inscribed basis contrasts with the literal meaning of the inscription.
                    Did Aias indeed erect a temple? It seems more likely that his votive offering
                    was an aedicula or even a miniature shrine, that would have stood on the basis
                    itself.</p>
            </div>
